  { q: 'How much does AC repair cost in Tampa?', a: 'Most Tampa AC repairs fall between $150 and $600 depending on the part. A capacitor or thermostat swap is on the lower end; refrigerant leak repair, evaporator coil or blower motor replacement is higher. We give every customer an upfront flat-rate quote before any work begins - no diagnostic surprises.' },
  { q: 'Can you repair my AC the same day?', a: 'Yes - we keep common parts (capacitors, contactors, fan motors, thermostats, standard refrigerant) on our Wesley Chapel service vans so most repairs are one-trip, same-day fixes. Specialty parts may take one business day to source.' },
  { q: 'Do you offer AC repair near me in Tampa Bay?', a: 'Very likely yes. We dispatch from Wesley Chapel and cover Wesley Chapel, New Tampa, Land O Lakes, Lutz, Odessa, Zephyrhills and all of Pasco, Hillsborough and Polk counties. Call (813) 395-2324 and we will confirm whether your address is on the route today.' },
  { q: 'What brands of AC do you service?', a: 'We service every major residential and light-commercial brand sold in Tampa Bay: Carrier, Trane, Lennox, Rheem, Goodman, American Standard, York, Amana, Bryant, Heil, Daikin and mini-split systems from Mitsubishi, LG and Fujitsu.' },
  { q: 'My AC is frozen - can I keep running it?', a: 'No. Shut it off and run the fan-only mode for 1–2 hours to thaw the coil, then call us. A frozen evaporator is almost always caused by low refrigerant, a dirty filter, or airflow blockage. Running a frozen system damages the compressor - the most expensive component.' },
  { q: 'Should I repair or replace my AC? (The $5,000 rule)', a: 'The industry rule of thumb is to multiply the age of your HVAC unit by the estimated repair cost. If the result exceeds $5,000, replacement usually wins on a 5-year operating-cost basis. Example: a 12-year-old system with a $500 repair = $6,000 - time to price replacement. A 6-year-old system with the same $500 repair = $3,000 - fix it and keep going. We show you both numbers on the same invoice so you can decide with real math, not a sales pitch.' },
  { q: 'What is the 3-minute rule for AC?', a: 'Wait at least three minutes before turning your AC back on after it shuts off. That pause lets refrigerant pressures equalize in the compressor. Restarting sooner forces the compressor to start against high head pressure - the fastest way to wear out or burn out the most expensive component in your system.' },
  { q: 'What\'s the best thermostat setting for summer in Wesley Chapel or Tampa?', a: 'The Florida sweet spot is 77–78°F when home, 74–76°F when sleeping, and 80–82°F when the house is empty. Above 82°F unoccupied isn\'t worth it - your system works overtime catching back up. Pair the setpoint with a humidity target of 45–55% RH for comfort at any temperature.' },
  { q: 'Do you warranty your AC repairs?', a: 'Every repair we make is backed by a 1-year parts-and-labor warranty on our workmanship. Manufacturer part warranties run on top of that - typically 5 years on most major components.' },
];

