  <h2>Signs it's time to call for AC repair</h2>
  <p>Small AC problems rarely fix themselves in Florida - they snowball into compressor damage and a hot house. Call us when you notice any of these:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Warm or weak air</strong> from the vents while the system is running.</li>
    <li><strong>The unit runs nonstop</strong> but never reaches the thermostat setpoint.</li>
    <li><strong>Short cycling</strong> - it turns on and off every few minutes.</li>
    <li><strong>Water or ice</strong> around the indoor air handler or on the refrigerant lines.</li>
    <li><strong>Burning, musty, or electrical smells</strong> when the system kicks on.</li>
    <li><strong>A sudden jump in your power bill</strong> with no change in how you use the AC.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>If the system is completely dead in dangerous heat, that is an <a href="/services/emergency-ac-repair-tampa/">emergency AC repair</a> - call us right away and we prioritize no-cool homes. For a deeper walkthrough, see our guide to the <a href="/blogs/10-most-common-ac-problems-wesley-chapel-homes/">10 most common AC problems in Wesley Chapel homes</a>.</p>

  <h2>Common AC problems we fix every week in Wesley Chapel &amp; Tampa</h2>
  <p>Tampa Bay's humidity and near-constant summer runtime put residential AC systems under harder stress than almost anywhere else in the country. The problems we see most often in Wesley Chapel and the surrounding neighborhoods:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>AC blowing warm air.</strong> Usually a low-refrigerant leak, failed capacitor, or frozen evaporator coil. <a href="/blogs/ac-blowing-warm-air-in-tampa-heres-how-to-fix-it-fast/">Full troubleshooting guide →</a></li>
    <li><strong>System runs but won't cool.</strong> Almost always a dirty condenser coil, refrigerant charge issue, or a failing compressor. <a href="/blogs/air-conditioning-not-cooling-in-tampa-fl-heres-how-to-fix-it-fast/">See our Tampa guide →</a></li>
    <li><strong>Loud grinding, buzzing, or clicking.</strong> Bad contactor, blower wheel out of balance, or a failing compressor bearing. Never ignore - it almost always gets worse fast.</li>
    <li><strong>Water pooling at the indoor unit.</strong> Clogged condensate drain, rusted pan, or frozen coil dripping as it thaws. We clear, flush and treat the line every service call.</li>
    <li><strong>Short cycling.</strong> Thermostat placement, oversized equipment, or a failing low-voltage control board. We diagnose with manifold gauges and a thermal imaging check before quoting.</li>
    <li><strong>High electric bills with no cooling change.</strong> Typically a dying compressor pulling locked-rotor amps, a dirty coil, or refrigerant undercharge.</li>
  </ul>

